# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: broomball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:broomball/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:broomball/200-foot-game] A **200-foot game** is a definition in ice hockey that describes a player's (usually a forward's) ability to have strong presence in all three zones of an ice rink, which is standardized at 200 feet long.
[src:broomball/200-foot-game] Players who can play a 200-foot game are contrasted with players who score a lot of points by avoiding hard forechecking or backchecking, cherry picking their plays perhaps for breakaways, and avoiding fighting for the puck in the corners of the rink, such as Pavel Bure or Brett Hull.
[src:broomball/200-foot-game] Playing a 200-foot game means fighting for each part of the ice, fighting for control of the puck whether it's in one's possession or not, and engaging using your body in traffic.
[src:broomball/200-foot-game] Classic examples of players who exemplify the 200-foot player include Gordie Howe, Bryan Trottier, Jari Kurri, Steve Yzerman, Patrice Bergeron, Doug Gilmour, Pavel Datsyuk, Mike Modano, Bobby Clarke, Sergei Fedorov, Joe Sakic, Anže Kopitar, Bob Gainey, Frank Nighbor, Ryan Getzlaf and Sidney Crosby.
[src:broomball/200-foot-game] Having players able to play a 200-foot game is widely considered a key to success in the modern game.
[src:broomball/200-foot-game] The term can also be used to refer to defencemen who are also skilled offensive players (such as Bobby Orr and Nicklas Lidström), as well as coaches that employ a balanced style of play.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 has been a basketball format long played in streets and gyms across the world, albeit in a less formal way.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] Starting in the late 2000s, 3x3 game rules started to become standardized throughout the United States, most notably through the Gus Macker and Hoop It Up tournament series, which held large events across the country that included teams and players from all skill levels.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] In 1992, Adidas launched its now-discontinued streetball competition.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] Since then, the number of 3x3 events and competitions has been steadily growing around the world.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] A Romanian organization, Sport Arena Streetball, began hosting 3x3 events in Bucharest as early as 2005, helping to grow the sport locally and regionally before formal FIBA rules were introduced.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] FIBA first test 3x3 at the 2007 Asian Indoor Games in Macau, followed by further test events in April 2008 in the Dominican Republic and October 2008 in Indonesia.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The international debut of 3x3 under FIBA rules occurred at the 2009 Asian Youth Games, where 19 teams competed in the boys' tournament and 16 teams competed in the girls' tournament, with all games held at Anglican High School in Tanah Merah, Singapore.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 made its worldwide competitive debut at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics in Singapore, where 20 teams competed in both boys' and girls' categories, with games held at the Youth Space.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] Since then, FIBA has regularly held world championships in both open and U18 categories.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] Bucharest, later called the "Mecca of 3x3 basketball" by Sports Illustrated, hosted the first FIBA Europe 3x3 Championships in 2014, an event that helped establish organized 3x3 competition across Europe.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] In subsequent years, the city also hosted international 3x3 tournaments, attracting teams from outside Europe.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] FIBA developed 3x3 as a standalone discipline with its own format and regular international competitions.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made its Olympic debut at the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The 3x3 basketball variation has also been used in several tournaments, such as the Nike 3ON3 Tournament and Spokane Hoopfest, the largest 3x3 basketball tournament in the world, held annually in Spokane, Washington.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] FIBA releases from time-to-time a supplement to its official basketball rules specifically for 3x3.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The rules state that regular FIBA rules apply to all situations not specifically addressed in the FIBA 3x3 rules.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The current set, both in an abbreviated version and longer format, was published in August 2019.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The current rules depart from regular full-court basketball in the following ways.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] Each team consists of three players and one substitute.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] Each team must have three players on the court when the game begins.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The game is played on a half-court with one basket.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The American NBA & WNBA standard half-court distance is 15.24 m (50 ft) wide & 14.33 m (47 ft) long.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The ball is the size of a size 6 basketball (720 mm, 28.5 in) as used in the women's full-court game and its mass is that of the size 7 standard (620 g, 22 oz) used in the men's full-court game.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] A coin toss is held immediately before the game, and the winning team of the coin flip can choose to take possession of the ball at the start of the game, or take the first possession of a potential overtime period.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] In turn, this means that if the game goes into overtime, the first possession goes to the team that started the game on defense.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The game begins with the defensive team passing the ball to the offensive team to signify the start of the game.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] All offensive players must begin outside of the arc (the opposite side of the arc of the net), and the defensive team must begin inside of the arc.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] Once the offensive team receives the ball, the clock starts.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] This exchange is also used to restart the game from any dead ball situation.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The game is a single period of a maximum 10 minutes and the winner is the first team to score 21 or the team with the higher score at the end of the 10 minutes; scoring 21 points immediately ends the game.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] Every successful shot inside the arc, including free throws, is awarded one point, while every successful shot outside of the arc ("downtown") is awarded two points.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] After a made goal or free throw (except for technical or unsportsmanlike fouls and team fouls 10 or more; see below), play restarts with a player from the non-scoring team taking the ball directly under the basket and then dribbling or passing it to a point behind the arc.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The defense is not allowed to play for the ball inside the block/charge semi-circle under the basket.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] In any held-ball situation, the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The offensive team must attempt a shot for a goal within 12 seconds.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] An offensive player may also not dribble inside the arc with their back or side to the basket for more than 3 consecutive seconds.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] For either violation the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] There is a Trent Tucker Rule in which with up to 0.2 seconds left in regulation or on the shot clock, a high lob, or tip-in must be made.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] A tie in regulation time leads to an untimed overtime period, after a one-minute intermission.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] Whichever team began the game as the defensive team, begins overtime as the offensive team.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The first team to score two points wins the game.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] Note: if a game is tied at 20 at the end of regulation, a team scoring their 21st point in overtime does not end the game.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] Substitutions can occur only in a dead-ball situation; a substitute can only enter from behind the end line opposite the basket, and the substitution becomes official once the player leaving the game has "tagged up" by making physical contact with the substitute.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] Each team is allowed one 30 second time-out per game.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] Each personal or technical foul counts as one team foul, while each unsportsmanlike or disqualifying foul counts as two team fouls.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] Personal fouls during the act of shooting inside the arc are awarded one free throw, while fouls during the act of shooting behind the arc and the shot is unsuccessful are awarded two free throws.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] Team fouls 7, 8 and 9 are awarded two free throws, and all team fouls thereafter are awarded two free throws and possession of the ball.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The "bonus" rule specifically supersedes the normal rule for fouls in the act of shooting.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The un-timed overtime period is considered extension of regulation for purpose of team fouls.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The first unsportsmanlike foul against a player results in two free throws.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] A second unsportsmanlike foul, or a disqualifying foul, results in two free throws and possession.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] A player who commits two unsportsmanlike fouls is disqualified.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] A team loses the game by default if all of its players are disqualified.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] All technical fouls result in one free throw, with possession going to the team that was entitled to possession at that time.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] If a foul is committed that results in the non-fouling team retaining possession, i.e. a technical or "unsportsmanlike" foul, the non-fouling team will receive the exchange outside of the arc.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] Offensive fouls, if not technical, unsportsmanlike, or disqualifying, never result in free throws, regardless of the number of team fouls.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] In the case of a double foul, no free throws are awarded to either team, regardless of team foul count or whether the double fouls were unsportsmanlike.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] FIBA sees 3x3 as a major vehicle for promotion of the game of basketball throughout the world.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] FIBA Secretary General and IOC member Patrick Baumann explained: "The 3x3 concept has all the elements and skills required for basketball, it has inspired and will continue to inspire many great players in the future.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] At the same time, it is the easiest and one of the most-effective ways to bring youngsters to basketball, keep them and promote our game.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] FIBA is pursuing a strategy to implement 3x3.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] FIBA has developed a digital community that acts as a repository for all FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events worldwide and offers all players an individual world ranking based on the points earned by players at FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] Any event around the world can become FIBA-endorsed by using FIBA's freeware, EventMaker, to organise the event.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] All FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events are classified within an established competition hierarchy, thus forming an official competition network.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The pinnacle of this competition network is the FIBA 3x3 World Tour, which includes a series of World Tour Masters and one Final.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] A team can qualify for a World Tour Masters by playing in any of the designated World Tour qualifiers.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The North American National Basketball Association (NBA) has also embraced 3x3.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] Since 2016, the NBA has held a summer series of tournaments known as "Dew NBA 3X", where local amateur players from around the US compete in regional events for cash prizes and a finals berth.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The men's and women's NBA 3X champions then advance to the USA Basketball national 3x3 championship to potentially represent their country internationally.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] These tournaments also include live music performances, 3-point shooting contests for fans, an *NBA 2K* eSports competition, and appearances from current NBA players.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The qualification system for the FIBA 3x3 World Cups for men and women differs radically from the system used for FIBA full-court competitions.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] According to *The New York Times*, 3x3 has "an unusual qualifying system designed to grow the sport all year long as much as find the best teams for the World Cup." National team entries are based strictly on a country's official 3x3 ranking.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The ranking system for national teams also considers individual player rankings.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] For example, the US women's team qualified for the 2018 World Cup while the men's team did not, even though the men were ranked higher than the women on the cutoff date.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] Participating in a FIBA-sanctioned 3x3 event can earn ranking points; according to a FIBA executive, "Andorra has heavy participation every weekend." The current concentration of ranking events in Europe makes it more difficult for non-European nations, especially the US, to qualify.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The aforementioned FIBA executive, when asked about the prospect of the 2020 Olympic debut of 3x3 potentially lacking any participation from the US, admitted that "a lot of teams want to beat the US.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] After the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics, FIBA established a regular World Cup that always includes men and women competing simultaneously in open, U23 and U18 categories.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] World Cups are played every year, except in years when there are Youth Olympic Games or Olympic Games.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] The COVID-19 pandemic caused the cancellation of the 2020 event.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] Classification to the World Cup is based on the 3x3 Federation Ranking, which ranks all National Federations based on the 3x3 Individual World Ranking points of their top 100 nationals in the respective category (i.e. men, women, U23 men, U23 women, U18 men, and U18 women).
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball became a regular European Games contest since its introduction at the 2015 European Games in Baku, Azerbaijan.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made a debut in Olympic programme for the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo, Japan, for both men and women.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball was included in 2022 Commonwealth Games in Birmingham, England.
[src:broomball/3x3-basketball] After the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, FIBA banned Russian teams and officials from participating in FIBA 3x3 Basketball competitions.
[src:broomball/aflx] The AFL held two official Australian Football League (AFL) pre-season AFLX competitions featuring senior AFL clubs and players, in 2018 and 2019, but these were unpopular with spectators and did not return in 2020.
[src:broomball/aflx] The variation continues to be promoted by the AFL Commission as a participation sport in development regions and areas, and particularly where full-sized cricket grounds are not available.
[src:broomball/aflx] Since the COVID-19 pandemic, AFLX has been merged with AFL 9s and retained only the X brand, co-branding AFL 9s as Junior X, Youth X and Senior X and aligning it with the more widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:broomball/aflx] The rules of the game differed from standard Australian rules football in some significant ways.
[src:broomball/aflx] The game was played on a rectangular soccer-sized pitch, allowing matches to be hosted by stadiums that usually lacked the suitable field dimensions for Australian rules football.
[src:broomball/aflx] AFLX was first trialled at Arden Street Oval in January 2017.
[src:broomball/aflx] Two months later, it was trialed at was first trialled on a soccer pitch at Lakeside Stadium in a match between the Port Melbourne Football Club and Coburg Football Club.
[src:broomball/aflx] AFLX pre-season competition was launched by AFL chief executive officer Gillon McLachlan at Docklands Stadium on 6 February 2018.
[src:broomball/aflx] McLachlan said that AFLX would help promote football internationally.
[src:broomball/aflx] The 2018 competition attracted more than 40,000 fans to tournaments in Adelaide, Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:broomball/aflx] In Melbourne, TV ratings were reported as "modest" by AFL standards, with the three events drawing an average five-city metro audience of over 120,000 on Channel Seven's secondary channels.
[src:broomball/aflx] The AFL made several rule tweaks midway through the second season in attempt to make it higher scoring by inflating the scoring points for behinds from 1 to 2, goals from 6 to 12 and Super Goals from 10 to 20.
[src:broomball/aflx] Whitten Legends Game was also played under "EJX" (modified version of AFLX named after E J Whitten) at AAMI Park in Melbourne.
[src:broomball/aflx] It attracted just 6,000 spectators, the lowest in the series history.
[src:broomball/aflx] AFLX did not return as a senior AFL competition in 2020, as AFL had a greater focus on AFLW.
[src:broomball/aflx] Post the COVID-19 pandemic, the AFL increased the number of players to 9, effectively merging AFLX with AFL 9s and aligning with the widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:broomball/aflx] The reception to the two AFL pre-season competitions among fans and the media was mostly poor, with ABC Radio Grandstand journalist Richard Hinds being particularly savage in labelling it a "hollow, unappealing, pressure-free, atmosphere-deficient, oval-in-a-rectangle hole yawn-fest".
[src:broomball/aflx] Con Stavros of RMIT's school of Economics, Finance and Marketing, expressed doubts about the potential of AFLX to export Australian rules football but acknowledged that using rectangular playing fields instead of the standard cricket ones would make such expansion easier.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Although similar to paintball in concept and gameplay, airsoft pellets do not leave visible dye markings on their target and hits are not always apparent, though the pellets can sometimes leave small bruises or welts on exposed skin (and so protective gear is still recommended).
[src:broomball/airsoft] The game therefore relies heavily on an honor system in which players who have been hit are expected to call themselves out of play in keeping with honesty, fairness and sportsmanship.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The airsoft guns used are mostly magazine-fed, with some having manual/battery motor-powered spring-piston pump power plants similar to Nerf Blasters, or pneumatically powered by replaceable compressed gas (e.g. propane ("green gas"), 1,1,1,2-tetrafluoroethane or CO2) canisters.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Many airsoft guns also have mounting platforms compatible with genuine firearm accessories, and most cosmetically resemble real firearms.
[src:broomball/airsoft] This makes them popular for military simulation and historical reenactments.
[src:broomball/airsoft] There are also professional gun safety and weapon manipulation training conducted with airsoft in some fields, such as law enforcement training, due to better safety and lower cost.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The United States Coast Guard, for instance, officially adopted airsoft for training in 2018.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Airsoft gameplay varies in style and composition, but often ranges from action shooting to short organized live action role-playing (LARP) scenarios, close quarters battle skirmishes, military simulations (MilSim) or historical reenactments.
[src:broomball/airsoft] It is played in indoor courses or outdoor fields.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Combat situations on the field may involve the use of genuine military tactics to achieve objectives set in each game.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Participants may attempt to emulate the tactical equipment and accessories used by modern military and police organizations.
[src:broomball/airsoft] A game is normally kept safe by trained professionals acting as supervisors and marshals.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Before gameplay, an airsoft gun's muzzle velocity is usually checked through a chronograph and usually measured in feet per second (FPS) or joules, a measurement for kinetic energy.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Some countries have a set velocity or muzzle energy restriction; guns shooting over the legal muzzle velocity can be confiscated.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Some playing fields further restrict minimum engagement distances, requiring players to yell "Bang Bang!" or other verbal phrases in order to prevent shooting other players at close distances, which may cause injury.
[src:broomball/airsoft] In certain countries use of laser sights of any kind is illegal, including gun scopes with integrated lasers.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Airsoft originated in postwar Japan during the early 1970s, when photographer Ichiro Nagata, an avid shooting enthusiast himself, thought about making modelguns that shoot real projectiles that could not kill or wound.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Early airsoft guns use a manual spring-piston design and are essentially single-shot, tailoring to the needs of shooting enthusiasts while conforming to Japan's strict weapons control laws.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Originally designed for target shooting, the plastic balls used in these "guns" can be shot at humans without causing injury due to the low muzzle energy.
[src:broomball/airsoft] These new-generation replica guns were trademarked as **soft air guns** because the refrigerant propellant used was significantly weaker ("soft") than the canistered CO2 used in proper airguns (pellet guns and BB guns).
[src:broomball/airsoft] This practical convenience of AEGs led soft air guns to quickly become popular for casual MilSim games, which the Japanese call **survival games** (サバイバルゲーム, *sabaibaru gēmu*).
[src:broomball/airsoft] Asahi Firearms was also a model company from Japan who operated in the 1980s and 90s and was one of the early pioneers of the airsoft hobby.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Airsoft guns spread to the United Kingdom in the late 1980s and early 1990s via a company called LS.
[src:broomball/airsoft] They were sold in separate pieces and had to be assembled out-of-box before they were capable of shooting.
[src:broomball/airsoft] These then became available to the rest of Europe and North America and rapidly gained popularity worldwide.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Since the mid-1980s, airsoft has been adapted with a purely recreational application in mind, and the sport is enjoyed by all ages.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Airsoft replicas are produced globally, with the majority being manufactured in East Asia.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Many law enforcement agencies and military units within the United States now start using airsoft for force-on-force tactical training drills.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The guns used in airsoft are typically classified as imitation firearms.
[src:broomball/airsoft] They have a mechanism for shooting projectiles 6 mm, 6.4 mm, or 8 mm in diameter.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Some companies produce full replicas of counterpart grenade launchers which fire a projectile spray of 6 millimetres (0.24 in) pellets by use of a high-powered spring mechanism or a compressed gas propellant (i.e. green gas, propane, compressed air, or CO2).
[src:broomball/airsoft] There is also a type of airsoft gun that is powered by a single (HPA) high-pressure air tank and a battery pack to power the internal FCU "Fire Control Unit" computer board.
[src:broomball/airsoft] These guns are often known for their high and adjustable RPS or "Rounds Per Second" and durability.
[src:broomball/airsoft] These HPA replicas are most often referred to as "PolarStars", although this refers to a popular brand of HPA engines and accessories.
[src:broomball/airsoft] A typical airsoft gun is noticeably lighter than its "real steel" counterpart due to the use of aluminum alloy and plastic materials, though some have added weights in them for a more realistic feel.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Japan has specific rules about producing airsoft guns with metal parts, while newer guns, especially those made in Taiwan and Mainland China, have both internal and external parts that are metallic.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Smoke caps, as well as noise amplifiers, are available for certain airsoft guns to add realism.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Gas handgun magazines usually contain 10 to 30 pellets in a standard-capacity magazine; however, some are high-capacity magazines and can hold 50 rounds or more.
[src:broomball/airsoft] In the case of AEG rifles, magazines come in either real-capacity (equivalent to the 30-round capacity of its real steel counterpart), low-capacity (10–50 rounds), mid-capacity (75–250 rounds), or high-capacity (250+ rounds).
[src:broomball/airsoft] These magazines have spring followers like in BB guns.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The high-cap magazines often have a ratchet wheel that can be wound up periodically to force pellets up from the holding chamber of the magazine to the feeding chute.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Due to loose pellets in the reservoir, they often make a rattling noise when running or walking.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Some airsoft guns have a battery-powered box or drum magazine that holds thousands of pellets, but these are usually only used and allowed on LMGs (light machine gun) type replicas.
[src:broomball/airsoft] It is common for owners to "tech" (modify) their guns.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The majority of gearboxes are made to Tokyo Marui specifications and have aftermarket upgrade parts available commercially.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Some gearboxes are proprietary in design.
[src:broomball/airsoft] It is also possible to perform DIY modifications.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The "hop-up" system, which is installed in most stock airsoft rifles and pistols, is used to increase effective ranges by putting backspin on the pellets.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The Magnus effect causes the pellets to experience more lift as they are shot, counteracting against gravity.
[src:broomball/airsoft] A small rubber nub protrudes into the top of the barrel through a small hole, applies pressure on a rubber bucking, and catches the top of the pellet as it moves past.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Adjusting the hop-up makes the nub more or less protrude into the bucking, so that backspin is increased or reduced.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Ideally, the hop-up should be adjusted so that the pellets fly as far as possible in a straight line without curving upward too far or dropping too quickly.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Hop-Up does decrease the muzzle velocity (a gun firing 340 ft/s (100 m/s) with the hop fully unwound can drop to as low as 300 ft/s (91 m/s)).
[src:broomball/airsoft] Ease and location of adjustment vary by gun design; some equipment provides a control that can be adjusted quickly during gameplay, while others may require partial disassembly.
[src:broomball/airsoft] For example, a common location for Hop-Up adjustment is where the ejection port would be on a real firearm, which allows the machine to be covered while still allowing quick access to adjust the Hop-Up.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Some players customize their airsoft guns, either to improve performance or for purely aesthetic reasons.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Additions include scopes, fore-grips, and flashlights, red dot sights being the most commonly used.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Red dot sights are used to help aim, fore-grips are used to get a better grip on the airsoft gun, and flashlights (whether mounted or held in another hand) are used to illuminate dark areas and/or to blind opponents.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Even though in certain countries lasers are illegal, they are popular attachments in the U.S. and Europe.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Also available are "mock suppressors/silencers".
[src:broomball/airsoft] These resemble the actual firearm accessory that dampens sound.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Since Airsoft does not use combustibles for propulsion these usually serve no function.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Although there are models that function to "light up" a glow-in-the-dark BB using UV light similar to a tracer round.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Most airsoft guns fire round plastic pellets, usually white, but Tracers are common as well.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The pellets mostly range from 0.12 to 0.48 g.
[src:broomball/airsoft] However, the most popular weights for AEGs (automatic electric guns) and GBB* (Gas Blow-Back guns) are 0.20 g to 0.32 g (whose muzzle velocity ranges from approximately 250 ft/s (76 m/s) to 400 ft/s (120 m/s)).
[src:broomball/airsoft] Heavier rounds (0.36–0.40 g) are typically used in long-range and sniper applications since they are more stable in flight and less easily deflected by wind.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The pellets, which are called BBs (ball bearings), are usually bought in bags or bottles of 2,000 to 5,000, but other sizes are available, such as a 250,000 round (65 kg) package of tournament grade BBs.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Biodegradable BBs are a fraction more expensive than non-bio counterparts, but many fields require them.
[src:broomball/airsoft] BBs are typically 5.95mm ±0.01 mm in diameter.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Due to the low muzzle energy (less than 1.5 J or 1.1 ft⋅lb even for high-power models) and poor sectional density, the pain an airsoft pellet causes on skin impact is about the same as getting pinched.
[src:broomball/airsoft] As a reference value, a standard 0.20 gram 6 mm pellet, which is the most common size and weight, traveling at 100 m/s (330 ft/s) has 1 J (0.74 ft⋅lb) of kinetic energy.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Calculating the kinetic energy of an airsoft projectile is important for ensuring player safety.
[src:broomball/airsoft] While a projectile’s ability to cause injury or penetrate a surface technically depends on energy density—that is, the kinetic energy divided by the impact area—this variable is nearly constant in airsoft, as most BBs have standardized diameters of 6 mm or 8 mm.
[src:broomball/airsoft] As a result, the primary factor affecting the potential for injury or penetration is simply the kinetic energy of the BB.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Despite this, safety limits in airsoft are often expressed solely in FPS, which fails to account for variations in BB mass.
[src:broomball/airsoft] where m is the mass in kilograms and v is the speed in meters per second.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Different regions vary in the velocity airsoft guns are allowed to shoot at.
[src:broomball/airsoft] In the United States, velocity differs from the type of gameplay field.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Close Quarter Battle arenas typically regulate velocity on airsoft guns at around 110 m/s (350 ft/s).
[src:broomball/airsoft] For outdoor fields, velocity is usually regulated by the type of gun.
[src:broomball/airsoft] With a standard 0.20 grams (3.1 gr) pellet, fully automatic Airsoft Electric Guns (AEGs) are often set at less than 120 m/s (400 ft/s), semi-automatic DMR-style AEGs at 120–140 m/s (400–450 ft/s), and bolt-action (manually cocked spring-piston) sniper rifles at 140–150 m/s (450–500 ft/s).
[src:broomball/airsoft] The maximum effective range of field-legal airsoft guns is around 100 m (110 yd) with a highly upgraded sniper rifle replica.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Most airsoft guns used for field play will have an effective range of around 43–67 m (47–73 yd), depending on the intended gameplay role.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Most Airsoft guns are capable of shooting from 60 to 125 m/s (200 to 410 ft/s), although it is also possible to purchase upgraded internals that will enable the gun to shoot up to 170 m/s (550 ft/s) or higher.
[src:broomball/airsoft] In California, a common limit for CQB is 110 m/s (350 ft/s).
[src:broomball/airsoft] In Ireland, Italy and Japan the muzzle energy limit for airsoft guns is 1 joule no matter what the type of gameplay.
[src:broomball/airsoft] In the UK, the law allows weapons locked to semi-automatic and bolt-action rifles to fire up to 2.5 joules (at muzzle velocity up to 158 m/s or 518 ft/s).
[src:broomball/airsoft] Any weapon "which is capable of discharging two or more missiles successively without repeated pressure on the trigger" is limited, by law, at 1.3 joules (velocity up to 114 m/s or 374 ft/s).
[src:broomball/airsoft] Northern Ireland has a maximum velocity of 100 m/s (330 ft/s) with 0.20 g pellets, without regard to the type of equipment.
[src:broomball/airsoft] In Sweden, the legal limitations of airsoft guns caps the energy limit at 10 joules for manual guns, and 3 joules for semi- and fully automatic guns.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The ballistics of spring- or electrically powered airsoft guns differ from real firearms in that a longer barrel will not always result in better accuracy.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The "sweet spot" for barrel length in a spring/electric powered airsoft gun is around 450 mm (18 in), beyond which added barrel length will not improve accuracy.
[src:broomball/airsoft] In any case, barrel quality, velocity consistency, and hopup quality/design are more important factors with regard to accuracy.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Added barrel length will result in slightly increased velocity if the cylinder size and compression are appropriate for the barrel length.
[src:broomball/airsoft] For example, a gun with a large cylinder and a long barrel will shoot slightly harder than a gun with a small cylinder and a short barrel (*ceteris paribus*).
[src:broomball/airsoft] This rule will apply even for barrels longer than 500 mm (20 in), if there is enough cylinder volume and air compression to propel the pellet through the barrel.
[src:broomball/airsoft] However, the resulting velocity increase will be hardly noticeable.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The only considerable advantage of using a longer inner barrel in an AEG or spring-powered gun is that it generally will make the gun quieter due to the weakened muzzle pop.
[src:broomball/airsoft] In gas-powered guns, added barrel length (to an appropriate extent) can result in increased velocity and accuracy to a degree.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Tighter-bore barrels will increase velocity because there will be less space between the pellet and the barrel for the air to escape through.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Most stock airsoft guns have 6.03–6.05 mm (0.237–0.238 in) bore barrels, but best performance is usually seen with "tightbore" barrels, which are 6.01–6.05 mm (0.237–0.238 in) in diameter.
[src:broomball/airsoft] However, the tighter the bore, the more likely the chance of a pellet jam, and subsequently, tightbores need to be cleaned and lubricated regularly.
[src:broomball/airsoft] It is generally agreed upon that a high-quality 6.01-6.02 mm barrel will provide the highest muzzle velocity, while a good-quality 6.03 mm or 6.05 mm barrel will provide the best compromise between power, accuracy and ease of maintenance.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The actual accuracy difference between tightbore sizes is debatable and usually outweighed by bore consistency.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Although, with the newfound popularity with HPA guns, the debate has been opened that barrels with a larger diameter (up to 6.13 mm or 0.241 in) could provide a more accurate shot.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Due to the higher volume of air surrounding the pellet it negates the chance of the pellet coming into contact with the barrel, throwing the pellet's trajectory off, similar to a musket, in how the bullet slams about before leaving the barrel.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Airsoft guns are not to be confused with BB guns, which are airguns that shoot 4.5 mm (.177 in) metallic spherical pellets, unlike the plastic pellets shot by airsoft guns.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Many manufacturers and retailers suggest treating an airsoft gun like a real gun at all times.
[src:broomball/airsoft] This will help alleviate safety issues resulting in an accidental/negligent discharge, or prevent a public panic due to a carelessly displayed airsoft gun being mistaken for a real firearm.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Most manufacturers include an orange tip on the muzzle of the airsoft gun for signaling and safety purposes, and most retailers urge consumers not to remove the orange tip as it is used to help distinguish them from a real firearm.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The orange tip serves many purposes, one of them being for law enforcement to help discern airsoft guns from real firearms and thus prevent unnecessary excessive forces.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The minimum safe level of gear required to participate in most games includes a pair of ANSI Z87.1 eye protection, preferably a fully sealed APEL-rated ballistic eyewear.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Traditional prescription glasses and sunglasses, or goggles not rated sufficiently for impact-resistance, may shatter and/or be perforated upon being struck when used for airsoft or paintball, causing injury to the eye.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Masks, face shields and other types of full-face coverings such as balaclavas are recommended at most airsoft fields.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Rules such as a maximum muzzle velocity and engagement distance guidelines are used by different groups.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Some organizations have created common safety rules and guidelines.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Most minimum engagement distances are 10 feet (3.0 m).
[src:broomball/airsoft] When not actively playing, some fields require "barrel bags", also known as barrel socks, barrel condoms, barrel blockers, or barrel sleeves, to be placed over the muzzle of the gun.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The magazine is usually removed as well, and the gun fired to clear the chamber.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Most fields also require players to leave their guns set to the safety position when they are not shooting, a practice common when using real firearms.
[src:broomball/airsoft] In certain countries, such as the Philippines, additional special rules have been adopted.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Airsoft is legal in most parts of the world.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Some countries have specific restrictions, such as maximum muzzle velocity and "unrealistic" coloring to distinguish them from actual firearms.
[src:broomball/airsoft] They are legal throughout the United States, but restrictions do exist in cities like Chicago and Detroit.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The states of New Mexico, New York and New Jersey, however, do not allow airsoft guns to be used or handled publicly because of the resemblance to real firearms.
[src:broomball/airsoft] They may be used on private property with the consent of the owner.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Customs and Border Protection FAQ page states that Airsoft guns are considered look-alike firearms which require the special blaze orange marking.
[src:broomball/airsoft] In Ireland, Airsoft guns are classified as Realistic Imitation Firearms but not restricted as much as in the United Kingdom.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Under the Criminal Justice Act of 2006, Airsoft guns are legal in the Republic.
[src:broomball/airsoft] One can buy, sell and import Airsoft guns without notifying relevant law enforcement authorities.
[src:broomball/airsoft] They do not need to be painted in fluorescent colours, they do not need to have an orange tip, but they cannot launch the projectile with a kinetic energy exceeding 1 joule.
[src:broomball/airsoft] However, carrying an imitation firearm in public is prohibited, and a gun carry case is required, as for real firearms.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Airsoft shops are spread over the country, and buyers must be aged 18 or over to purchase an airsoft gun.
[src:broomball/airsoft] There is no age limit on Airsoft, as long as a minor has an adult's permission.
[src:broomball/airsoft] In the United Kingdom, most Airsoft guns are classified as realistic imitation firearms or RIFs.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The sale, manufacture, or importation (but not gifting) of these is illegal under the Violent Crime Reduction Act 2006.
[src:broomball/airsoft] A defence is allowed for selling for specific purposes including airsoft skirmishing.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The minimum age for buying any imitation firearm in the UK is 18.
[src:broomball/airsoft] It is an offence to possess an imitation firearm in a public place without a reasonable excuse, for example traveling to, or from, or being at an airsoft skirmish site.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Most UK airsoft sites and retailers participate in the United Kingdom Airsoft Retailer Association Ltd (UKARA) registration scheme.
[src:broomball/airsoft] A player who has participated in at least 3 skirmishes over a period of at least 56 days at the same skirmish site can be registered by that site.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Retailers have access to the database to verify that the purchaser can provide them with a defence.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The Border Agency also has access to check legality of imports.
[src:broomball/airsoft] As an alternative to RIFs, IFs (Imitation Firearms, including 'two tones') are available in the UK.
[src:broomball/airsoft] These are RIFs which have been painted a bright colour (excluding white/silver/gold) over at least 51% of the item.
[src:broomball/airsoft] No specific defence is required for selling an IF, although the minimum age for purchasing remains 18.
[src:broomball/airsoft] In Canada, there are laws pertaining to airsoft importing.
[src:broomball/airsoft] All airsoft guns that are bought in Canada are legal, but when importing it, the gun has to have between 366FPS and 500FPS to pass inspection at customs, otherwise the gun will be shipped back or destroyed.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Airsoft guns in the United States are sold with a federally mandated orange tip which must be 1/4 inch or longer covering the muzzle of the replica.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Airsoft technology is used in military training and law enforcement training.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Due to airsoft's realism, relatively safe projectiles, and economical ammunition, it is well-suited to war games and force-on-force scenarios to train and improve troop's tactical proficiency via associative learning and stress inoculation.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Multiple airsoft inventions were developed originally for military and law enforcement use.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Marking rounds were invented by Kerry T.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Bowden to allow trainees to see where each projectile landed.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Much like paintball and simunitions, these marking pellets would break upon impact, marking the target with luminescent liquid.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Unlike traditional plastic pellets, marking rounds are heavier to ensure breakage of the shell on impact.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The weight can be adjusted by adding heavier liquid.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Marking rounds are critical for trainees because they allow the shooter to see exactly where they hit the target.
[src:broomball/airsoft] This allows them to extrapolate their mistakes and improve their aim.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Reusable grenades were improved by Scott Frank to emulate the fragmentation of a real grenade in war games and scenarios.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The grenade can be loaded with paint or pellets.
[src:broomball/airsoft] It uses a quick release of highly pressurized gas to break the shell and quickly disperse pellets or paint in all directions.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Frank's grenade, although not the first, aimed to be as realistic and predictable as an actual grenade.
[src:broomball/airsoft] He developed a more accurate timing mechanism and secondary safety mechanisms to prevent accidental discharge.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Both marking rounds and reusable grenades gave airsoft the edge it needed to enter into military and law enforcement training grounds.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The airsoft guns used for training differ from civilian models.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Guns manufactured for professional training are made to replicate the weight, feel and the sound of its real steel counterpart.
[src:broomball/airsoft] In general, professional training airsoft guns are GBB models and enhanced with a weighted blowback mechanism to increase the force of the kick.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Some are AEGs and are built with a blowback mechanism.
[src:broomball/airsoft] They are also outfitted with muzzle protectors that amplify the sound to a decibel level comparable to that of a real firearm.
[src:broomball/airsoft] The average FPS for professional training airsoft guns is higher than civilian models.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Economically, airsoft is cheaper than simulation training.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Benjamin Kratz, Fort Jackson's battalion executive officer, said that one blank M16 round can cost as much as 32 airsoft rounds.
[src:broomball/airsoft] Airsoft can also be used in military simulations such as in malls or prisons to add to the immersion.
[src:broomball/airsoft] There are different event producers like MiR Tactical holding these events.
[src:broomball/american-flag-rugby] American flag rugby is divided up among four different levels based upon the grade level a child is entering.
[src:broomball/american-flag-rugby] Each division itself has a unique set of rules in recognition that there will be different ability levels between the various age groups.
[src:broomball/american-flag-rugby] The game, while based on rugby union, is actually far more related to rugby sevens.
[src:broomball/american-flag-rugby] Similarities are seen with the number of players on the field and the arrangement of the line-outs, scrums and kick-offs.
[src:broomball/american-flag-rugby] Like rugby union, games are played in halves but the halves are significantly reduced.
[src:broomball/american-flag-rugby] The halves are the same for all four levels at 10 minutes each instead of 40 minutes each.
[src:broomball/american-flag-rugby] The rule differences between each division are minor and gradually shift closer towards rugby union rules as the child advances up in divisions and increases his or her skill set.
[src:broomball/american-flag-rugby] For Owls the game typically revolves around teaching the children to run with the ball, learning to touch the ball down when scoring a try and learning basic passing skills.
[src:broomball/american-flag-rugby] Nothing is contested, there is no kicking, and there are no conversions.
[src:broomball/american-flag-rugby] However, when children reach the Eagle level, many of the prior mentioned restrictions are removed and the children play with contest are allowed open field kicking, and the game has a more dynamic flow to it.
[src:broomball/american-flag-rugby] The first iteration of American flag rugby was founded by Tom Feury in 1998.
[src:broomball/american-flag-rugby] Feury was initially looking for nothing more than a way to get his children and their friends introduced to the game.
[src:broomball/american-flag-rugby] In 1999, the town of Denville granted him access to a field in order to do so.
[src:broomball/american-flag-rugby] The first year began with only one team and 28 children.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] American football evolved in the United States, originating from the sports of soccer and rugby.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The first American football game was played on November 6, 1869, between two college teams, Rutgers and Princeton, using rules based on the rules of soccer at the time; by 1875, the sport had adopted rules similar to rugby union.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] A set of rule changes drawn up from 1880 onward by Walter Camp, the "Father of American Football", established concepts that would define the sport, among them the snap, the line of scrimmage, eleven-player teams, and the concept of downs.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Later rule changes legalized the forward pass, created the neutral zone, and specified the size and shape of the football.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The modern sport is closely related to Canadian football, which evolved in parallel with and at the same time as the American game; the two sports are considered the primary variants of gridiron football.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] American football is the most popular sport in the United States; the most popular forms of the game are professional and college football, with the other major levels being high school and youth football.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Over a million Americans played college or high school football in 2022, and the National Football League (NFL) has one of the highest average attendance of any professional sports league in the world.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Its championship game, the Super Bowl, ranks among the most-watched club sporting events globally.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Other professional and amateur leagues exist worldwide, but the sport does not have the international popularity of other American sports like baseball or basketball; the sport maintains a growing following in the rest of North America, Europe, Brazil, and Japan.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Flag football, a variant of the sport, will be played at the 2028 Summer Olympics.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] In the United States, American football is referred to as "football".
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The term "football" was officially established in the rulebook for the 1876 college football season, when the sport first shifted from soccer-style rules to rugby-style rules.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Although it could easily have been called "rugby" at this point, Harvard, one of the primary proponents of the rugby-style game, compromised and did not request the name of the sport be changed to "rugby".
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The terms "gridiron" or "American football" are favored in English-speaking countries where other types of football are popular, such as the United Kingdom, Ireland, New Zealand, and Australia.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] American football evolved from the sports of rugby and soccer.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Rugby, like American football, is a sport in which two competing teams vie for control of a ball, which can be kicked through a set of goalposts or run into the opponent's goal area to score points.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] What is considered to be the first American football game was played on November 6, 1869, between Rutgers and Princeton, two college teams.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] They consisted of 25 players per team and used a round ball that could not be picked up or carried.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] It could, however, be kicked or batted with the feet, hands, head, or sides, with the objective being to advance it into the opponent's goal.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Collegiate play continued for several years with games played using the rules of the host school.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Representatives of Yale, Columbia, Princeton and Rutgers met on October 19, 1873, to create a standard set of rules for use by all schools.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Teams were set at 20 players each, and fields of 400 by 250 feet (122 m × 76 m) were specified.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Harvard abstained from the conference, as they favored a rugby-style game that allowed running with the ball.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] An 1875 Harvard–Yale game played under rugby-style rules was observed by two Princeton athletes who were impressed by it.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] They introduced the sport to Princeton, a feat the Professional Football Researchers Association compared to "selling refrigerators to Eskimos".
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Princeton, Harvard, Yale, and Columbia then agreed to intercollegiate play using a form of rugby union rules with a modified scoring system.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] These schools formed the Intercollegiate Football Association, although Yale did not join until 1879.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Yale player Walter Camp, now regarded as the "Father of American Football", secured rule changes in 1880 that reduced the size of each team from 15 to 11 players and instituted the snap to replace the chaotic and inconsistent scrum.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] While the game between Rutgers and Princeton is commonly considered the first American football game, several years prior in 1862, the Oneida Football Club formed as the oldest known football club in the United States.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The team consisted of graduates of Boston's elite preparatory schools and played from 1862 to 1865.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The introduction of the snap resulted in an unexpected consequence.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Before the snap, the strategy had been to punt if a scrum resulted in a bad field position.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] However, a group of Princeton players realized that, as the snap was uncontested, they could now hold the ball indefinitely to prevent their opponent from scoring.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] In 1881, in a game between Yale and Princeton, both teams used this strategy to maintain their undefeated records.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Each team held the ball, gaining no ground, for an entire half, resulting in a 0–0 tie.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] This "block game" proved extremely unpopular with both teams' spectators and fans.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] A rule change was necessary to prevent this strategy from taking hold, and a reversion to the scrum was considered.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] However, Camp successfully proposed a rule in 1882 that limited each team to three downs, or tackles, to advance the ball 5 yards (4.6 m).
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Failure to advance the ball the required distance within those three downs would result in control of the ball being forfeited to the other team.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] This change effectively made American football a separate sport from rugby, and the resulting five-yard lines added to the field to measure distances made it resemble a gridiron in appearance.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Other major rule changes included a reduction of the field size to 110 by 53+1⁄3 yards (100.6 m × 48.8 m) and the adoption of a scoring system that awarded four points for a touchdown, two for a safety and a goal following a touchdown, and five for a goal from the field.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Additionally, tackling below the waist was legalized, and a static line of scrimmage was instituted.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Despite these new rules, football remained a violent sport.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Dangerous mass-formations like the flying wedge resulted in serious injuries and deaths.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] A 1905 peak of 19 fatalities nationwide resulted in a threat by President Theodore Roosevelt to abolish the game unless major changes were made.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] In response, 62 colleges and universities met in New York City to discuss rule changes on December 28, 1905.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] These proceedings resulted in the formation of the Intercollegiate Athletic Association of the United States, later renamed the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA).
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The legal forward pass was introduced in 1906, although its effect was initially minimal due to the restrictions placed on its use.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The idea of a 40-yard-wider field was opposed by Harvard due to the size of the new Harvard Stadium.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Other rule changes introduced that year included the reduction of playing time from 70 to 60 minutes and an increase of the distance required for a first down from 5 to 10 yards (4.6 to 9.1 m).
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] To reduce infighting and dirty play between teams, the neutral zone was created along the width of the football before the snap.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Scoring was also adjusted: points awarded for field goals were reduced to three in 1909 and points for touchdowns were raised to six in 1912.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Also in 1912, the field was shortened to 100 yards (91 m) long, two 10-yard-long (9.1 m) end zones were created, and teams were given four downs instead of three to advance the ball 10 yards (9.1 m).
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The roughing the passer penalty was implemented in 1914, and eligible players were first allowed to catch the ball anywhere on the field in 1918.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] On November 12, 1892, Pudge Heffelfinger was paid $500 (equivalent to $17,917 in 2025) to play a game for the Allegheny Athletic Association against the Pittsburgh Athletic Club.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Despite these extra benefits, the game had a strict sense of amateurism at the time, and direct payment to players was frowned upon, if not prohibited outright.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Over time, professional play became increasingly common, and with it came rising salaries and unpredictable player movement, as well as the illegal payment of college players who were still in school.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The National Football League (NFL), a group of professional teams that was originally established in 1920 as the American Professional Football Association, aimed to solve these problems.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] This new league's stated goals included an end to bidding wars over players, prevention of the use of college players, and abolition of the practice of paying players to leave another team.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] By 1922, the NFL had established itself as America's premier professional football league.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The dominant form of football at the time was played at the collegiate level.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The upstart NFL received a boost to its legitimacy in 1925, however, when an NFL team, the Pottsville Maroons, defeated a team of Notre Dame all-stars in an exhibition game.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] A greater emphasis on the passing game helped professional football to distinguish itself further from the college game during the late 1930s.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Football, in general, became increasingly popular following the 1958 NFL Championship game between the Baltimore Colts and the New York Giants, still referred to as the "Greatest Game Ever Played".
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The game, a 23–17 overtime victory by the Colts, was seen by millions of television viewers and had a major influence on the popularity of the sport.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] By the mid-1960s, football was the most popular sport in the United States.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] In 1972, polling from Gallup, Inc. found that twice as many Americans identified football as their favorite sport (38%) as compared to baseball (19%); the sport has remained the most popular in the United States since.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] In 1960, the American Football League (AFL) was created to compete with the NFL.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The AFL began in relative obscurity but eventually thrived, with an initial television contract with the ABC television network.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The AFL's existence forced the conservative NFL to expand to Dallas and Minnesota in an attempt to destroy the new league.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Meanwhile, the AFL introduced many new features to professional football in the United States and actively recruited minority players.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The AFL also signed several star college players who had also been drafted by NFL teams.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Competition for players heated up in 1965, when the AFL New York Jets signed rookie Joe Namath to a then-record $437,000 contract (equivalent to $4.46 million in 2024).
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] A five-year, $40 million NBC television contract followed, which helped to sustain the young league.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The bidding war for players ended in 1966 when NFL owners approached the AFL regarding a merger, and the two leagues agreed on one that took full effect in 1970.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] This agreement provided for a common draft that would take place each year, and it instituted an annual World Championship game to be played between the champions of each league.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] This championship game, which would come to be known as the Super Bowl, began play at the end of the 1966 season.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Once the merger was completed, it was no longer a championship game between two leagues, instead being competed between the American Football Conference (AFC) and the National Football Conference (NFC).
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Prior to the 1956 college football season, NCAA schools were organized into an upper University Division and lower College Division.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] In the summer of 1973, the University Division became Division I, but by 1976, there was a desire to further separate the major football programs from those that were less financially successful, while still allowing their other sports to compete at the top level.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] In 1978, the NCAA divided Division I football into two subdivisions: NCAA Division I-A (known today as the Football Bowl Subdivision, or FBS) and Division I-AA (known today as the Football Championship Subdivision, or FCS).
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The FCS adopted a single-elimination playoff structure to determine its champion, while the FBS retained its tradition of postseason bowl games.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Each bowl game was associated with a particular conference, and earning a spot in a major bowl game was the reward for winning a conference.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] This arrangement was beneficial to both conferences and bowl games, but it generally prevented the top-ranked teams from meeting in a true national championship game.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Because the NCAA itself does not officially sanction a Division I-FBS national champion, FBS national champions prior to 1992 were determined by polls, which frequently led to controversial or "split" national champions.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] In 1992, the Bowl Coalition was created to determine the national champion.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] It was replaced in 1995 by the Bowl Alliance, which itself gave way to the Bowl Championship Series (BCS) in 1997.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] All three of these systems consisted of a single national championship game, as well as a set of other major bowl games.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] In 2014, the BCS was replaced by the College Football Playoff (CFP), a single-elimination tournament.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] In another major change, in 2021, following legal pressure and antitrust lawsuits, the NCAA and its conferences began allowing schools to offer compensation to student athletes for the use of their names, images, and likenesses (NIL).
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] NCAA* allowed schools to directly pay players, ending the traditionally amateur nature of college athletics in the United States.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] A football game is played between two teams of 11 players each.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Playing with more on the field is punishable by a penalty.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Teams may substitute any number of their players between downs; this "platoon" system has resulted in teams utilizing specialized offensive, defensive and special teams units.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The number of players allowed on an active roster varies by league; the NFL has a 53-man roster, while NCAA Division I allows teams to have up to 105 players on their roster.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Individual players in a football game must be designated with a uniform number between 0 and 99.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] NFL teams are required to number their players by a league-approved numbering system, and any exceptions must be approved by the commissioner.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] NCAA and NFHS teams are "strongly advised" to number their offensive players according to a league-suggested numbering scheme.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Women are eligible to play in high school, college, and professional football, but most football players are men.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] No woman has ever played in the NFL, but women have played in high school and college football games.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] In 2018, women and girls comprised 0.5% of players in Pop Warner Little Scholars youth football, 0.2% of players in high school football, and 10.9% of Americans who report playing tackle football.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The role of the offensive unit is to advance the football down the field with the ultimate goal of scoring a touchdown.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The offensive team must line up in a legal formation before they can snap the ball.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] An offensive formation is considered illegal if there are more than four players in the backfield or fewer than five players numbered 50–79 on the offensive line.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Players can line up temporarily in a position whose eligibility is different from what their number permits as long as they report the change immediately to the referee, who then informs the defensive team of the change.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Neither team's players, except the center (C), are allowed to line up in or cross the neutral zone until the ball is snapped.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Interior offensive linemen are not allowed to move until the snap of the ball.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The main backfield positions are the quarterback (QB), running back (RB), and fullback (FB).
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The quarterback is the leader of the offense.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Either the quarterback or a coach calls the plays.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Quarterbacks typically inform the rest of the offense of the play in the huddle before the team lines up.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The quarterback lines up behind the center to take the snap and then hands the ball off, throws it, or runs with it.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The primary role of the running back is to carry the ball on running plays.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Fullbacks tend to be larger than halfbacks and function primarily as blockers, but they are sometimes used as runners in short-yardage or goal-line situations.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The offensive line (OL) consists of several players whose primary function is to block members of the defensive line from tackling the ball carrier on running plays or sacking the quarterback on passing plays.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The most important role on the offensive line is the center, who is not just responsible for blocking and snapping the ball, but also for handling line adjustments and pre-snap strategy.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] On either side of the center are the guards (G), while tackles (T) line up outside the guards.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The principal receivers are the wide receivers (WR) and the tight ends (TE).
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Wide receivers line up on or near the line of scrimmage, split outside the line.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The main goal of the wide receiver is to catch passes thrown by the quarterback, but they may also function as decoys or as blockers during running plays.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Tight ends line up next to the offensive line and function both as receivers and as blockers.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The role of the defense is to prevent the offense from scoring by tackling the ball carrier or by forcing turnovers.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Turnovers include interceptions (a defender catching a forward pass intended for the offense) and forced fumbles (taking possession of the ball from the ball-carrier).
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The defensive line (DL) consists of defensive ends (DE) and defensive tackles (DT).
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Defensive ends line up on the ends of the defensive line, while defensive tackles line up on the inside, between the defensive ends.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The primary responsibilities of defensive ends and defensive tackles are to stop running plays on the outside and inside, respectively, to pressure the quarterback on passing plays, and to occupy the line so that the linebackers can break through.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Linebackers line up behind the defensive line but in front of the defensive backfield.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] They are divided into two types: middle linebackers (MLB) and outside linebackers (OLB).
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Linebackers tend to serve as the defensive leaders and call the defensive plays, given their vantage point of the offensive backfield.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Their roles include defending the run, pressuring the quarterback, and tackling backs, wide receivers, and tight ends.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The defensive backfield, often called the secondary, consists of cornerbacks (CB) and safeties (S).
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Safeties are themselves divided into free safeties (FS) and strong safeties (SS).
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Cornerbacks line up outside the defensive formation, typically opposite a receiver to be able to cover them.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Safeties line up between the cornerbacks but farther back in the secondary.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Safeties tend to be viewed as "the last line of defense" and are responsible for stopping deep passing plays as well as breakout running plays.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The special teams unit is responsible for all kicking plays.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The special teams unit of the team in control of the ball tries to execute field goal (FG) attempts, punts, and kickoffs, while the opposing team's unit will aim to block or return them.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Three positions are specific to the field goal and PAT (point after touchdown) unit: the placekicker (K or PK), holder (H), and long snapper (LS).
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The long snapper's job is to snap the football to the holder, who will catch and place it on the ground for the kicker.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] There is usually never a holder on kickoffs, because the ball is kicked off a tee; however, a holder may be used in certain situations, such as if wind is preventing the ball from remaining upright on the tee.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The player on the receiving team who catches the ball is known as the kick returner (KR).
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The positions specific to punt plays are the punter (P), long snapper, upback, and gunner.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The long snapper snaps the football directly to the punter, who then drops and kicks it before it hits the ground.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Gunners line up split outside the line and race down the field, aiming to tackle the punt returner (PR)—the player who catches the punt.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Upbacks line up a short distance, typically 1-7 yards, behind the line of scrimmage, providing additional protection to the punter.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] In football, the winner is the team that has scored more points at the end of the game.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] There are multiple ways to score in a football game.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The touchdown (TD), worth six points, is the most valuable scoring play.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] A touchdown is scored when a live ball is advanced into, caught, or recovered in the opposing team's end zone.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The scoring team then attempts a try, more commonly known as the point(s)-after-touchdown (PAT) or conversion, which is a single scoring opportunity.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] If the PAT is scored by a place kick or drop kick through the goal posts, it is worth one point, typically called the extra point.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] If the PAT is scored by what would normally be a touchdown, it is worth two points; this is known as a two-point conversion.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] In general, the extra point is almost always successful, while the two-point conversion is a much riskier play with a higher probability of failure; accordingly, extra point attempts are far more common than two-point conversion attempts.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] A field goal (FG), worth three points, is scored when the ball is place kicked or drop kicked through the uprights and over the crossbars of the defense's goalposts.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Almost all field goal attempts are done via place kick.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] While drop kicks were common in the early days of the sport, the shape of modern footballs makes it difficult to reliably drop kick the ball.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The last successful scoring play by drop kick in the NFL was accomplished in 2006; prior to that, the last successful drop kick had been made in 1941.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] After a PAT attempt or successful field goal, the scoring team must kick the ball off to the other team.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] A safety is scored when the ball carrier is tackled in the carrier's own end zone.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Safeties are worth two points, which are awarded to the defense.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] In addition, the team that conceded the safety must kick the ball to the scoring team via a free kick.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Safeties are the least common method of scoring in football.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Football games are played on a rectangular field that measures 120 yards (110 m) long and 53+1⁄3 yards (48.8 m) wide.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Lines marked along the ends and sides of the field are known as the end lines and sidelines.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Goal lines are marked 10 yards (9.1 m) inward from each end line.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Weighted pylons are placed along each sideline, on the inside corner of the intersections with the goal lines and end lines.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] White markings on the field identify the distance from the end zone.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Inbound lines, or hash marks, are short parallel lines that mark off 1-yard (0.91 m) increments.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Yard lines, which can run the width of the field, are marked every 5 yards (4.6 m).
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] A one-yard-wide line is placed at each end of the field; this line is marked at the center of the two-yard line in professional play and at the three-yard line in college play.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Numerals that display the distance from the closest goal line in yards are placed on both sides of the field every ten yards.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Goalposts are located at the center of the plane of the two end lines.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The crossbar of these posts is 10 feet (3.0 m) above the ground, with vertical uprights at the end of the crossbar 18 feet 6 inches (5.64 m) apart for professional and collegiate play, and 23 feet 4 inches (7.11 m) apart for high school play.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The uprights extend vertically 35 feet (11 m) on professional fields, a minimum of 10 yards (9.1 m) on college fields, and a minimum of 10 feet (3.0 m) on high school fields.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Goal posts are padded at the base, and orange ribbons are normally placed at the tip of each upright as indicators of wind strength and direction.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The football itself is a prolate spheroid leather ball, similar to the balls used in rugby or Australian rules football.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] At all levels of play, the football is inflated to 12+1⁄2 to 13+1⁄2 psi (86 to 93 kPa), or just under one atmosphere, and weighs 14 to 15 ounces (400 to 430 g); beyond that, the exact dimensions vary slightly.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] In professional play the ball has a long axis of 11 to 11+1⁄4 inches (28 to 29 cm), a long circumference of 28 to 28+1⁄2 inches (71 to 72 cm), and a short circumference of 21 to 21+1⁄4 inches (53 to 54 cm).
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] In college and high school play the ball has a long axis of 10+7⁄8 to 11+7⁄16 inches (27.6 to 29.1 cm), a long circumference of 27+3⁄4 to 28+1⁄2 inches (70 to 72 cm), and a short circumference of 20+3⁄4 to 21+1⁄4 inches (53 to 54 cm).
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Football games last for a total of 60 minutes in professional and college play and are divided into two halves of 30 minutes and four quarters of 15 minutes.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] High school football games are 48 minutes in length with two halves of 24 minutes and four quarters of 12 minutes.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The two halves are separated by a halftime period, and the first and third quarters are followed by a short break.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Before the game starts, the referee and each team's captain meet at midfield for a coin toss.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The visiting team can call either "heads" or "tails"; the winner of the toss chooses whether to receive or kick off the ball or which goal they wish to defend.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] They can defer their choice until the second half.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Unless the winning team decides to defer, the losing team chooses the option the winning team did not select—to receive, kick, or select a goal to defend to begin the second half.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Most teams choose to receive or defer, because choosing to kick the ball to start the game allows the other team to choose which goal to defend.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Teams switch goals following the first and third quarters.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] If a down is in progress when a quarter ends, play continues until the down is completed.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] If certain fouls are committed during play while time has expired, the quarter may be extended through an untimed down.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Games last longer than their defined length due to play stoppages—the average NFL game lasts slightly over three hours.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Time in a football game is measured by the game clock.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] An operator is responsible for starting, stopping and operating the game clock based on the direction of the appropriate official.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] A separate play clock is used to show the amount of time within which the offense must initiate a play.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The play clock is set to 25 seconds after certain administrative stoppages in play and to 40 seconds when play is proceeding without such stoppages.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] If the offense fails to start a play before the play clock reads "00", a delay of game foul is called on the offense.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] There are two main ways the offense can advance the ball: running and passing.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] In a typical play, the center passes the ball backwards and between their legs to the quarterback in a process known as the snap.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The quarterback then either hands the ball off to a running back, throws the ball, or runs with it.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The play ends when the player with the ball is tackled or goes out-of-bounds or a pass hits the ground without a player having caught it.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] A forward pass can be legally attempted only if the passer is behind the line of scrimmage; only one forward pass can be attempted per down.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] As in rugby, players can also pass the ball backwards at any point during a play.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] In the NFL, a down also ends immediately if the runner's helmet comes off.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The offense is given a series of four plays, known as downs.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] If the offense advances ten or more yards in the four downs, they are awarded a new set of four downs.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] If they fail to advance ten yards, possession of the football is turned over to the defense.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] In most situations, if the offense reaches their fourth down they will punt the ball to the other team, which forces them to begin their drive from farther down the field; if they are in field goal range, they might attempt to score a field goal instead.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] A group of officials, the chain crew, keeps track of both the downs and the distance measurements.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The spot needed to secure a first down is known as the line to gain.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] On television, a yellow line is electronically superimposed on the field to show the line to gain to the viewing audience.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] There are two categories of kicks in football: scrimmage kicks, which can be executed by the offensive team on any down from behind or on the line of scrimmage, and free kicks.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The free kicks are the kickoff, which starts the first and third quarters and overtime and follows a try attempt or a successful field goal, and the safety kick, which follows a safety.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] On a kickoff, the ball is placed at the 35-yard line of the kicking team in professional and college play and at the 40-yard line in high school play.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The ball may be drop kicked or place kicked.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] If a place kick is chosen, the ball can be placed on the ground or a tee; a holder may be used in either case.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] On a safety kick, the kicking team kicks the ball from their own 20-yard line.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] They can punt, drop kick or place kick the ball, but a tee may not be used in professional play.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Any member of the receiving team may catch or advance the ball.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The ball may be recovered by the kicking team once it has gone at least ten yards and has touched the ground or has been touched by any member of the receiving team.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The three types of scrimmage kicks are place kicks, drop kicks, and punts.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Only place kicks and drop kicks can score points.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The place kick is the standard method used to score points, because the pointy shape of the football makes it difficult to reliably drop kick.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Once the ball has been kicked from a scrimmage kick, it can be advanced by the kicking team only if it is caught or recovered behind the line of scrimmage.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] If it is touched or recovered by the kicking team beyond this line, it becomes dead at the spot where it was touched.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The kicking team is prohibited from interfering with the receiver's opportunity to catch the ball.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The receiving team has the option of signaling for a fair catch, which prohibits the defense from blocking into or tackling the receiver.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The play ends as soon as the ball is caught, and the ball may not be advanced.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Officials are responsible for enforcing game rules and monitoring the clock.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] All officials carry a whistle and wear black-and-white striped shirts and black hats, except for the referee, whose hat is white.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Each carries a weighted yellow flag that is thrown to the ground to signal that a foul has been called.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] An official who spots multiple fouls will throw their hat as a secondary signal.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Women can serve as officials; Sarah Thomas became the NFL's first female official in 2015.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Another set of officials, the chain crew, are responsible for moving the chains.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The chains, consisting of two large sticks with a 10-yard-long chain between them, are used to measure for a first down.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The chain crew stays on the sidelines during the game, but if requested by the officials, they will briefly bring the chains onto the field to measure.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] A typical chain crew will have at least three people—two members of the chain crew will hold either of the two sticks, while a third will hold the down marker.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The down marker, a large stick with a dial on it, is flipped after each play to indicate the current down and is typically moved to the approximate spot of the ball.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The chain crew system has been used for over 100 years and is considered an accurate measure of distance, rarely subject to criticism from either side.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Football is a full-contact sport, and injuries are relatively common.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Most injuries occur during training sessions, particularly ones that involve contact between players.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] To try to prevent injuries, players are required to wear a set of equipment.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] At a minimum players must wear a football helmet and a set of shoulder pads, but individual leagues may require additional padding such as thigh pads and guards, knee pads, chest protectors, and mouthguards.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Most injuries occur in the lower extremities, particularly in the knee, but a significant number also affect the upper extremities.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] The most common types of injuries are strains, sprains, bruises, fractures, dislocations, and concussions.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Repeated concussions (and possibly sub-concussive head impacts) can increase a person's risk in later life for CTE (chronic traumatic encephalopathy) and health issues such as dementia, Parkinson's disease, and depression.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Concussions are often caused by helmet-to-helmet or upper-body contact between opposing players, although helmets have prevented more serious injuries such as skull fractures.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] However, a study in the *Orthopaedic Journal of Sports Medicine* found that Heads Up Football was ineffective; the same study noted that more extensive reforms implemented by Pop Warner Little Scholars and its member teams were effective in significantly reducing concussion rates.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] A 2018 study performed by the VA Boston Healthcare System and the Boston University School of Medicine found that tackle football before age 12 was correlated with earlier onset of symptoms of CTE, but not with increased symptom severity.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] More specifically, each year a player played tackle football under age 12 predicted earlier onset of cognitive, behavioral, and mood problems by an average of two and a half years.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] To help mitigate injuries, the NCAA recommends limiting full contact (tackling to the ground) practices, avoiding full contact on consecutive days, and no more than 20 hours of practice per week.
[src:broomball/american-football-p01] Players must receive one day off per week.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The National Football League (NFL) and the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) are the most popular football leagues in the United States.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The National Football League was founded in 1920 and has since become the largest and most popular sport in the United States.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The NFL has the highest average attendance of any sporting league in the world, with an average attendance of 66,960 during the 2011 NFL season.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The NFL championship game is called the Super Bowl, and is among the biggest events in club sports worldwide.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] It is played between the champions of the National Football Conference (NFC) and the American Football Conference (AFC), and its winner is awarded the Vince Lombardi Trophy.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] College football is the third-most popular sport in the United States, behind professional football and professional baseball, respectively.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The NCAA, the largest collegiate organization, is divided into three Divisions: Division I, Division II and Division III.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Division I is the highest level of play, while Division III is the lowest; Division I and II programs can offer athletic scholarships to student-athletes, while Division III programs cannot.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Division I football is further divided into two subdivisions: the Football Bowl Subdivision (FBS) and the Football Championship Subdivision (FCS).
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The champions of each level of play are determined through playoff systems.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Other national college football organizations include the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics (NAIA), which comprises around 90 smaller colleges, and the National Junior College Athletic Association (NJCAA), whose membership consists of two-year colleges.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] High school football is the most popular sport in the United States played by boys.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The NFHS is the largest organization for high school football, with member associations in all 50 states as well as the District of Columbia.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] USA Football is the governing body for youth and amateur football, and Pop Warner Little Scholars is the largest organization for youth football.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The most successful league to directly compete with the NFL was the American Football League (AFL), which existed from 1960 to 1969.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The AFL became a significant rival in 1964 before signing a five-year, US$36 million television deal with NBC.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] AFL teams began signing NFL players to contracts, and the league's popularity grew to challenge that of the NFL.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The two leagues merged in the 1970 season, and all the AFL teams joined the NFL.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] An earlier league, the All-America Football Conference (AAFC), was in play from 1946 to 1949.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] After it had dissolved, two AAFC teams, the Cleveland Browns and the San Francisco 49ers, became members of the NFL; another member, the Baltimore Colts joined the league, but folded after just a year in the NFL.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Other attempts to start rival leagues since the AFL merged with the NFL in 1970 have been far less successful, as professional football salaries and the NFL's television contracts began to escalate out of the reach of competitors and the NFL covered more of the larger cities.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The World Football League (WFL) played for two seasons, in 1974 and 1975, but faced such severe monetary issues it could not pay its players.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] In its second and final season the WFL attempted to establish a stable credit rating, but the league disbanded before the season could be completed.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The United States Football League (USFL) operated for three seasons from 1983 to 1985.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Originally not intended as a rival league, the entry of owners who sought marquee talent and to challenge the NFL led to an escalation in salaries and ensuing financial losses.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] A subsequent US$1.5 billion antitrust lawsuit against the NFL was successful in court, but the league was awarded only $1 in damages, which was automatically tripled to $3 under antitrust law.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The original XFL, created in 2001 by WWE co-founder Vince McMahon, lasted for only one season.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Despite television contracts with NBC and UPN, and high expectations, the XFL suffered from low quality of play and poor reception for its use of tawdry professional wrestling gimmicks, which caused initially high ratings and attendance to collapse.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The United Football League (UFL) began in 2009 but folded after suspending its 2012 season after having lost $120 million over just three seasons.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Another spring league, the Alliance of American Football lasted less than one season, unable to keep investors.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] A revived United States Football League began play in 2022 and quickly faced immediate competition from the XFL, which resumed play in 2023.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The two leagues merged following the 2023 season, forming a new United Football League (UFL).
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] American football leagues exist throughout the world, but the game has yet to achieve the international success and popularity of baseball and basketball.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] At the international level, Canada, Mexico, and Japan are considered to be second-tier, while Austria, Germany, and France would rank among a third tier.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] These countries rank far below the United States, which is dominant at the international level.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] NFL Europa, the developmental league of the NFL, operated from 1991 to 1992 and then from 1995 to 2007.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] At the time of its closure, NFL Europa had five teams based in Germany and one in the Netherlands.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] In Germany, the German Football League (GFL) has 16 teams and has operated for over 40 seasons, with the league's championship game, the German Bowl, closing out each season.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The league operates in a promotion and relegation structure with German Football League 2 (GFL2), which also has 16 teams.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The United Kingdom also operated several teams within NFL Europe during the League's tenure.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The resulting rise in popularity of the sport brought the NFL back to the country in 2007 where they now hold the NFL International Series in London, currently consisting of four regular season games.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The continuing interest and growth in both the sport and the series has led to the possible formation of a potential NFL franchise in London.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] NFL commissioner Roger Goodell aims to host 16 international games each year, enough for each NFL team to play one international game each year.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] In the United Kingdom, the British American Football Association National Leagues (BAFANL), an amateur competition, is the top level of American football.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Teams compete across multiple levels in a promotion and relegation structure; the league's championship is the Britbowl.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] University competition is held through the British Universities American Football League (BUAFL), which was formed in 2007.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] In 2008, the league launched a partnership with the NFL, through its partner organization NFL UK.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] From 2007 to 2014, the BUAFL grew from 42 teams and 2,460 participants to 75 teams and over 4,100 people involved.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The standard form of American football is not an Olympic sport, but it was a demonstration sport at the 1932 Summer Olympics.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The International Federation of American Football (IFAF), an international governing body composed of continental federations, received provisional recognition from the International Olympic Committee (IOC) in 2014 and was fully recognized by the IOC in 2015.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] American football federations are present in Africa, the Americas, Asia, Europe, and Oceania; a total of 75 national football federations exist as of 2023.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The IFAF runs tournaments such as the IFAF World Championship, the IFAF Women's World Championship, the IFAF Junior World Championship, and the Flag Football World Championship.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Obstacles towards the goal of becoming an Olympic sport included the predominant participation of men in international play and the short three-week Olympic schedule.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Large team sizes were an additional difficulty, due to the Olympics' set limit of 10,500 athletes and coaches.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] American football also faced an issue with a lack of global visibility.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Nigel Melville, the CEO of USA Rugby, noted that "American football is recognized globally as a sport, but it's not played globally." To solve these concerns, major effort was put into promoting flag football, a modified version of American football, at the international level.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Flag football for men and women will debut as an Olympic sport at the 2028 Summer Olympics.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] "Baseball is still called the national pastime, but football is by far the more popular sport in American society", according to ESPN.com's Sean McAdam.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] In a 2014 poll conducted by Harris Interactive, professional football ranked as the most popular sport, and college football ranked third behind only professional football and baseball; 46% of participants ranked some form of the game as their favorite sport.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Professional football has ranked as the most popular sport in the poll since 1985, when it surpassed baseball for the first time.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Professional football is most popular among those who live in the eastern United States and rural areas, while college football is most popular in the southern United States and among people with graduate and post-graduate degrees.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Football is also the most-played sport by high school and college athletes in the United States.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] A 2022 survey from National Football Foundation found that one million high-school athletes played the sport, with another 81,000 college athletes across both the NCAA and the NAIA.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The Super Bowl is the most popular single-day sporting event in the United States, and is among the biggest club sporting events in the world in terms of TV viewership.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The NFL made approximately $12 billion in revenue in 2022.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Super Bowl games account for eight of the top ten most-watched broadcasts in American history; Super Bowl LVII, played on February 12, 2023, was watched by a record 115.1 million Americans, and is second only to the Apollo 11 moon landing (125 million viewers).
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The NFL is the most valuable sports league in the world, with the average team valued at over $8 billion.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] American football also plays a significant role in American culture.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The day on which the Super Bowl is held is considered a *de facto* national holiday, and in parts of the country like Texas, the sport has been compared to a religion.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Football is also linked to other holidays; New Year's Day is traditionally the date for several college football bowl games, including the Rose Bowl.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] However, if New Year's Day is on a Sunday, the bowl games are moved to another date so as not to conflict with the typical NFL Sunday schedule.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Thanksgiving football is another American tradition, hosting many high school, college, and professional games.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Implicit rules such as playing through pain and sacrificing for the better of the team are promoted in football culture.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] In Canada, the game has a significant following.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] According to a 2013 poll, 21% of respondents said they followed the NFL "very closely" or "fairly closely", making it the third-most followed league behind the National Hockey League (NHL) and Canadian Football League (CFL).
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] American football also has a long history in Mexico, which was introduced to the sport in 1896.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] It was the second-most popular sport in Mexico in the 1950s, with the game being particularly popular in colleges.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The *Los Angeles Times* notes the NFL claims over 16 million fans in Mexico, which places the country third behind the U.S. and Canada.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] American football is played in Mexico both professionally and as part of the college sports system.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] A professional league, the Liga de Fútbol Americano Profesional (LFA), was founded in 2016.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Japan was introduced to the sport in 1934 by Paul Rusch, a teacher and Christian missionary who helped to establish football teams at three universities in Tokyo.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Play was halted during World War II by order of Emperor Hirohito, but the sport began growing in popularity again after the war.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] As of 2010, there are more than 400 high school football teams in Japan, with over 15,000 participants, and over 100 teams play in the Kantoh Collegiate Football Association (KCFA).
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The X-League is the largest American football league in Japan, and the largest American football league in the world to use a promotion-relegation system.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Some teams in the X-League, like the Panasonic Impulse, are sponsored by corporations, and all Japanese players on these teams are employed by the corporation.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The league operates in separate spring and fall seasons, with each team playing five games.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The top eight teams make the playoffs, which are played in Tokyo Dome; the champion is determined by the Rice Bowl.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Europe is a major target for the expansion of the game by football organizers.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] In the United Kingdom in the 1980s, the sport was popular, with the 1986 Super Bowl being watched by over four million people (about 1 out of every 14 Britons).
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Its popularity faded during the 1990s, coinciding with the establishment of the Premier League—the top level of the English association football (soccer) league system.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] According to BBC America, there is a "social stigma" surrounding American football in the UK, with many Brits feeling the sport has no right to call itself "football" due to the lack of emphasis on kicking.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Nonetheless, the sport has retained a following in the United Kingdom; the NFL operates a media network in the country, and since 2007 has hosted the NFL International Series in London.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Super Bowl viewership has also rebounded, with over 4.4 million Britons watching Super Bowl XLVI.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The sport is played in European countries like Switzerland, which has American football clubs in every major city, and Germany, where the sport has around 45,000 registered amateur players.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] It was generally unknown there until the 1980s when a small group of players began playing on Copacabana Beach in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The sport grew gradually with 700 amateur players registering within 20 years.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Games were played on the beach with modified rules and without the traditional football equipment due to its lack of availability in Brazil.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Eventually, a tournament, the Carioca championship, was founded, with the championship Carioca Bowl played to determine a league champion.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The country saw its first full-pad game of football in October 2008.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] According to *The Rio Times*, the sport is one of the fastest-growing sports in Brazil and is almost as commonly played as soccer on the beaches of Copacabana and Botafogo.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Football in Brazil is governed by the Confederação Brasileira de Futebol Americano (CBFA), which had over 5,000 registered players as of November 2013.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The sport's increase in popularity has been attributed to games aired on ESPN, which began airing in Brazil in 1992 with Portuguese commentary.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The popularity and "easy accessibility" of non-contact versions of the sport in Brazil has led to a rise in participation by female players.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] According to ESPN, the American football audience in Brazil increased 800% between 2013 and 2016.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The network, along with Esporte Interativo, airs games there on cable television.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] NFL had expressed interest in having games in the country, eventually resulting in São Paulo's Arena Corinthians hosting Brazil's first NFL game in 2024, and the Super Bowl has become a widely watched event in Brazil at bars and movie theaters.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Further countries have also expressed interest in football to a lesser degree.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The Arab world has expressed growing interest in American football, with many countries in the region being members of IFAF Asia.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Jordan and the United Arab Emirates, which are not members of IFAF, have established their own domestic leagues.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Egypt established two leagues for the sport, namely the Egyptian League of American Football and the Egyptian Federation of American Football, and Saudi Arabia hosts two teams based out of Jeddah and Yanbu respectively.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] China has additionally been a target for the expansion of the sport, with the Mainland being the home of the Chinese National Football League as well as a growing audience of Super Bowl watchers.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Three franchises are also based out of Hong Kong, which prior to the COVID-19 pandemic regularly played mainland teams.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] NFL games average 900,000 viewers in China, though the league has cited logistical challenges which would prevent teams from playing games akin to abroad games in European countries.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Canadian football, the predominant form of football in Canada, is closely related to American football—both sports developed from rugby and are considered to be the chief variants of gridiron football.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The Canadian Football League (CFL) is the major Canadian league and is the second-most popular sporting league in Canada, behind the National Hockey League.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Football Canada is the governing body for amateur Canadian football, and is also member of the International Federation of American Football.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] NFL players have played in the CFL and vice versa; quarterback Warren Moon is the only player in both Canadian Football Hall of Fame and the Pro Football Hall of Fame.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The NFL and CFL had a formal working relationship from 1997 to 2006.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The CFL has a strategic partnership with two American football leagues, the German Football League (GFL) and the Liga de Futbol Americano Profesional (LFA).
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Rule changes announced in 2025 by the CFL will bring some elements of the sport closer to those of American football, while retaining the larger number of players, wider field, and three-down limit.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The Indoor Football League is an example of a prominent indoor league.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] The Arena Football League, which was founded in 1987 and ceased operations in 2019, was one of the longest-lived indoor football leagues.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] In 2004, the league was called "America's fifth major sport" by *ESPN The Magazine*.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Some schools that lack the enrollment numbers to run a competitive 11-man team choose to play nine-man, eight-man, or six-man football, which utilize modified rules to account for smaller team sizes.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] There are several non-contact variants of football, such as flag football.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] In flag football the ball-carrier is not tackled; instead, defenders aim to pull a flag tied around the ball-carrier's waist.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Flag football has become increasingly popular due to its lower likelihood of head injuries and its openness to female athletes; according to the NFL, which promotes flag football through NFL Flag, roughly 25% of flag football players are women and girls.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Another variant, touch football, simply requires the ball-carrier to be touched to be considered downed.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Depending on the rules used, a game of touch football may require the ball-carrier be touched with either one or two hands to be considered downed.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Wheelchair football is a parasport adapting the rules of football for people with physical disabilities.
[src:broomball/american-football-p02] Although it uses touch rules instead of tackling, wheelchair football isn't a non-contact sport; participants engage in both "big hits" and "physical blocks".
[src:broomball/broomball] Unlike most winter team sports played on ice, organized broomball does not use ice skates.
[src:broomball/broomball] Player footwear for formal play consists of shoes created specifically for broomball which are designed to improve a player's traction on the ice.
[src:broomball/broomball] Though the sport can be played outdoors on snow, organized broomball in the 21st century is primarily played on an ice hockey rink.
[src:broomball/broomball] Players hit a ball around the ice or snow with a stick.
[src:broomball/broomball] Players wear special rubber-soled shoes instead of skates, and the ice is prepared in such a way that it is smooth and dry to improve traction.
[src:broomball/broomball] The ball used differs based on location: The indoor ball is smooth while the outdoor ball has ridges and resembles a small soccer ball.
[src:broomball/broomball] In a game of broomball there are two teams, each consisting of six players: a goaltender and five others.
[src:broomball/broomball] The object of the game is to score more goals than the opponent.
[src:broomball/broomball] Goals are scored by hitting the ball into the opponent's net using a traditional broom or the more conventional paddle-shaped stick designed for the sport.
[src:broomball/broomball] Tactics and plays are similar to those used in sports such as ice hockey, roller hockey and floorball.
[src:broomball/broomball] The sport uses its own offside rules in both International Federation of Broomball Associations (IFBA) rules and American broomball rules, but both differ.
[src:broomball/broomball] While ice hockey goal nets are sometimes used, a regulation-sized broomball net is considerably larger by comparison.
[src:broomball/broomball] IFBA sanctioned games use a 5-by-7-foot (1.5 m × 2.1 m) net, while American broomball uses 6-by-8-foot (1.8 m × 2.4 m) nets.
[src:broomball/broomball] The sport involves organized competitions and events run by its international governing body, the IFBA.
[src:broomball/broomball] The national organization in Canada is Broomball Canada while in the United States the two main organizations are All Elite Broomball (AEB) and the United States Broomball Association (USBA).
[src:broomball/broomball] Every two years the IFBA holds the IFBA World Broomball Championships (also known as the Challenge Cup), an international event with teams from around the world.
[src:broomball/broomball] Historically, the championships have been dominated by the North American teams.
[src:broomball/broomball] A similar game called Moscow broomball is played in Russia.
[src:broomball/broomball] The sport is played on either an indoor or outdoor ice rink.
[src:broomball/broomball] Conventional play involves the use equipment designed specifically for broomball, though recreationally the traditional corn broom with tape is still used.
[src:broomball/broomball] A regulation broomball goal net is considerably larger than the one used in the sport of ice hockey, though conventional ice hockey nets are often used unofficially.
[src:broomball/broomball] A broomball game begins with a face-off.
[src:broomball/broomball] A typical game of broomball is broken up into two or three periods.
[src:broomball/broomball] Each team has a goaltender plus five other players, typically two defenders and three attackers (two forwards and one centre).
[src:broomball/broomball] If the ice surface is especially small, some leagues use fewer players on the ice.
[src:broomball/broomball] The object of the game is to score goals into the opponent's goal or net.
[src:broomball/broomball] The team with the most goals at the end of a game is declared the winner.
[src:broomball/broomball] In some tournaments, if the scores are tied after regular time, an additional overtime period is played to determine a winner.
[src:broomball/broomball] In the overtime period (in most cases), six players, three on each team, play five minutes without a goalie.
[src:broomball/broomball] The team to score more goals in the overtime period is declared the winner.
[src:broomball/broomball] In the event of another tie, a second overtime period may be played.
[src:broomball/broomball] In some games a shootout period will be played.
[src:broomball/broomball] The shooter has the choice to have the ball placed a specified distance from the net or, like in hockey, can play the ball from centre ice.
[src:broomball/broomball] Sport specific equipment involves broomball shoes, broomball sticks, and broomball balls.
[src:broomball/broomball] Equipment used is either traditional for an informal style of play, or a deliberately manufactured design created for modern, formal play.
[src:broomball/broomball] In competitive play, protective equipment for broomball is similar to that used in the sports of ice hockey and ringette with some sport specific equipment designed for broomball.
[src:broomball/broomball] In traditional play, a broom is literally a broom, usually a corn broom, with tape added to keep the bristles from fraying.
[src:broomball/broomball] In the modern game, a broomball stick has a shaft with a stylized hard plastic paddle at the end.
[src:broomball/broomball] Shoes designed specifically for broomball are available for purchase, but only for games played on ice.
[src:broomball/broomball] The soles are designed to give players traction on the ice.
[src:broomball/broomball] In informal play, players can use any type of ball, though a soccer ball is usually used.
[src:broomball/broomball] In more formal play, two types of balls are manufactured for use.
[src:broomball/broomball] An outdoor ball is usually the colour blue, while the indoor ball is the colour orange.
[src:broomball/broomball] Broomball goal nets have a different shape than those used in ice hockey and ringette and are larger.
[src:broomball/broomball] Goaltenders generally wear a full face cage in addition to thick padding on the legs, thighs, chest and shoulders.
[src:broomball/broomball] Goaltenders are permitted to use a *blocker*, a specially designed rectangular glove attachment that is used to block shots.
[src:broomball/broomball] A blocker is similar to those used by ice hockey and ringette goalies.
[src:broomball/broomball] Goalies must also wear a chest protector.
[src:broomball/broomball] Broomball games are controlled by two on-ice referees.
[src:broomball/broomball] Both referees have the same powers to call all penalties, off-sides, goals, and so on.
[src:broomball/broomball] There usually are off-ice officials as well, depending on the level of the game being played, including a scorekeeper, a timekeeper, a penalty timekeeper, and goal judges.
[src:broomball/broomball] Referees are generally required to wear black and white vertical-striped jerseys, with a red arm band on one arm.
[src:broomball/broomball] They use this arm to signal penalties throughout the game.
[src:broomball/broomball] There is no known fully accurate history of broomball.
[src:broomball/broomball] The exact origin of the sport has been difficult to pinpoint.
[src:broomball/broomball] The best estimates in regards to its origin involves the First Nations in Canada, who are believed to have passed the sport on to the settlers.
[src:broomball/broomball] The first known recorded broomball games in North America were a variant played on roller skates in New York City and Kentucky.
[src:broomball/broomball] The first documented play in Canada is at Perdue, Saskatchewan, on March 5, 1909, though the game has also been observed to have been played by organized girls teams in the province of Ontario in the early 1900s.
[src:broomball/broomball] The Canadian style of the game is believed to have spread south to the United States, becoming especially popular in Minnesota.
[src:broomball/broomball] In 1910 a group of men would gather and play on the ice by the docks in Duluth, Minnesota.
[src:broomball/broomball] By the 1960s a broomball community was thriving in Minnesota.
[src:broomball/broomball] Initially the sport used brooms, usually corn brooms, and an assortment of different types of balls which were bigger than a baseball but not larger than a soccer ball.
[src:broomball/broomball] The playing area for a game of broomball took place on either a snow-covered area or field, or on an area of ice created by frozen ponds, lakes, rivers and the like, until both enclosed indoor and outdoor ice rinks, usually ice hockey rinks using artificial ice became more prevalent.
[src:broomball/broomball] Today the game is played on snow mostly during organized winter festivals, but play using an ice surface, especially artificial ones, has grown in popularity and is the playing area more prevalently seen used today.
[src:broomball/broomball] In regards to equipment, sport specific sticks and balls are available and have been developed for the game with balls designed for both indoor and outdoor play, while protective equipment is similar to and sometimes identical to that found in the sport of ice hockey.
[src:broomball/broomball] Broomball gradually spread internationally over the following decades, and by the 1980s, organized broomball was being played in Australia, Japan, Sweden, Italy, Germany, and Switzerland.
[src:broomball/broomball] The International Federation of Broomball Associations (IFBA) is the world governing body of broomball.
[src:broomball/broomball] Every two years the IFBA runs the IFBA World Broomball Championships (also known as the Challenge Cup), an international event with teams from around the world.
[src:broomball/broomball] Historically, the championships have been dominated by the North Americans teams.
[src:broomball/broomball] Broomball has been gaining popularity internationally.
[src:broomball/broomball] The sport is now an established international recreational sport, played in many countries around the world.
[src:broomball/broomball] Canada and the United States are the "powerhouse" nations of the sport, with their local representative teams often battling in prestigious tournaments held annually across North America.
[src:broomball/broomball] In Japan, some top teams and players are attracted to regular tournaments.
[src:broomball/broomball] Australia holds its annual National Championships in centres across the country and is continually increasing its number of players in a country where ice sports are not considered popular.
[src:broomball/broomball] Switzerland and Italy regularly send representative teams to tournaments in North America.
[src:broomball/broomball] Other broomball nations include Finland, Germany, and Russia.
[src:broomball/broomball] There are two main differences between International Federation of Broomball Associations (IFBA) gameplay and American broomball gameplay: the way offside works, and the size of the net.
[src:broomball/broomball] The results of these rules are generally considered to effect the game by making both the score and the pace of play slightly slower under IFBA rules.
[src:broomball/broomball] Under *IFBA* rules, the red line (centre ice) is the only line used to determine offside.
[src:broomball/broomball] Once the offensive team clears the red line, the defense must work to get it back over the same line.
[src:broomball/broomball] In *American broomball*, a "floating blue line" is employed, meaning the offensive team must pass the blue line, and then the defense must work to get it back over the red line.
[src:broomball/broomball] The other major difference is the size of the goalnets.
[src:broomball/broomball] While there are other slight differences, these two are by far the most significant.
[src:broomball/broomball] Broomball is played at many universities and colleges, mostly in North America.
[src:broomball/broomball] Some leagues are competitive while others function as a social event.
[src:broomball/broomball] Broomball is played, with a slightly different ruleset, by expatriates in Moscow.
